This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with the unsupervised discovery of linguistic units directly from speech data. It also involves the use of deep neural networks for feature extraction and tokenization, which are common techniques in natural language processing. 

It could also belong to cs.SD (Sound) as it deals with speech data and the extraction of acoustic features. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category as the paper involves the use of machine learning techniques such as deep neural networks for feature extraction and tokenization. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a possible sub-category as the paper involves the use of AI techniques for unsupervised learning and feature extraction. 

Finally, cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is another possible sub-category as the paper involves the use of deep neural networks for feature extraction and tokenization.
